----------|\n| `apps/backend/.../route.ts` | 42 | True positive, prod path | **Fix** |\n| `packages/x/.../foo.test.ts` | 17 | True positive, test-only | **Fix** or carve out via `overrides` if pattern-wide |\n| `packages/y/.../bar.ts` | 8 | False positive (rule too broad) | **Refine rule** + add a `valid` test capturing this shape |\n| `apps/scripts/.../seed.ts` | 99 | Acceptable in non-prod path | **`eslint-disable` with `--` justification** (counts toward the 12 budget) |\n\nDecisions:\n- **True positive in production code** → fix it.\n- **True positive in non-production / build-time / test-only path that is genuinely fine** → either add an `overrides` carve-out in `factory.js` (preferred for whole categories like `*.test.*`, `**/scripts/**`, `schema.ts`) OR an inline `// eslint-disable-next-line factory/<rule> -- <reason>`. Inline disables count toward the budget in Step 4 and require codeowner approval (#13331).\n- **False positive (rule reports something it should not)** → add a new `valid` test case that captures the shape, then refine the rule until it passes. Re-run Step 3.\n\nLoop Step 2 ↔ Step 3 — every false positive becomes a new `valid` test case, every true negative the rule originally missed becomes a new `invalid` test case.\n\n### Step 4. Quality gate — keep iterating until the bar is met\n\nThe rule is **NOT ready** until ALL of these hold across the whole monorepo:\n\n- **False-positive disable rate < 10%**: fewer than 10% of the original violation set required `eslint-disable` to silence. If higher, the rule is over-broad — return to Step 2 and tighten it.\n- **Total `eslint-disable` count for this rule ≤ 12 across the entire repo**. If higher, the rule is wrong-shaped or the convention itself is too aggressive — stop and reconsider scope (perhaps narrow the rule, or split it, or ship as off-by-default-with-app-opt-in).\n- Rule unit tests pass: `cd packages/eslint-config && npm test`.\n- Each affected workspace is clean for: `npm run lint -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>`, `npm run typecheck -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>`, `npm run test -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>`.\n- `npm run knip` at repo root passes.\n\nIf any check fails, loop back. Do not proceed to Step 5 with a rule that needs many disables — that is the strongest signal the convention is wrong.\n\n### Step 5. Ship the PR via `create-pr`\n\nInvoke the `create-pr` skill. Pre-flight:\n- Branch has commits not on `dev`: `git log origin/dev..HEAD --oneline`\n- Branch is pushed.\n- Local verification (Step 4) is green.\n\nTitle format (Conventional Commits, mandatory in this repo):\n```\nfeat(eslint-config): add <rule-name> rule\n```\nUse `feat(eslint-config)` when the rule is new and ships from the eslint-config preset; use `feat(<scope>): new eslint rule to <verb>` when the rule is enabled in a single app's `.eslintrc.js` (precedent: `feat(backend): new eslint rule to ban nextjs error responses (#12638)`).\n\nBase branch: `dev` (always — `create-pr` skill enforces this).\n\n### Step 6. Structure the PR description from the best historical examples\n\nThe strongest exemplars in this repo are **#13116** (`no-deprecated-feature-flag-references`) and **#10770** (`no-shell-injection`). Mirror their shape:\n\n1. **One-line motivation** — what bad pattern this rule bans.\n2. **The concrete production hazard** — quote the prod regression, runtime crash, or security risk. Cite the issue / PR if there is one.\n   > Quote from #13116: *\"... this is exactly how the SlackAutoRunHeadless prod regression in #12893 made it past review.\"*\n3. **What is skipped / exempted** — test files, scripts, schema files, etc.\n4. **Verification statement listing the workspaces actually checked** — explicit, not vague.\n   > Quote from #13116: *\"Verified against the full backend, web, cli, scripts, desktop, common, and frontend workspaces -- zero existing production-code violations.\"*\n5. **Test coverage stat** — number of `valid`/`invalid` test cases.\n   > Quote from #10770: *\"15 test