            "content": "---\nname: create-lint-rule\ndescription: >\n  Author a new custom ESLint rule in @factory/eslint-config using a strict\n  TDD workflow, sweep the entire monorepo to fix every violation as a\n  guaranteed NOOP, and ship it as a PR. Use when you need to enforce a new\n  code-quality convention via lint. Not for fixing violations of existing\n  rules -- use ban-type-assertions, process-env-migration, no-use-effect,\n  or fix-knip-unused-exports instead.\n---\n\n# Create Lint Rule\n\nAuthor a new `factory/<rule-name>` ESLint rule, sweep the monorepo to zero existing violations, and ship the PR. The workflow is strict TDD: tests come from the ticket verbatim, then implementation, then a triaged repo-wide sweep, then a hard quality gate.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- You need to enforce a new code-quality convention via lint.\n- You have BAD/GOOD examples in a ticket or design doc that describe the convention.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- Fixing violations of an already-existing rule -- use the dedicated fix skills:\n  - `ban-type-assertions` -- replace `as` casts.\n  - `process-env-migration` -- migrate `process.env` to `@factory/environment`.\n  - `no-use-effect` -- replace `useEffect` calls.\n  - `fix-knip-unused-exports` -- fix knip unused-exports violations.\n- Tweaking an existing custom rule -- edit the rule + its test file directly.\n\n## Quick Reference\n\n| Where | What |\n| --- | --- |\n| `packages/eslint-config/rules/<name>.js` | Rule source |\n| `packages/eslint-config/rules/<name>.test.js` | RuleTester unit tests |\n| `packages/eslint-config/rules/index.js` | Rule registration |\n| `packages/eslint-config/factory.js` | Base preset wiring |\n| `packages/eslint-config/plugin.js` | `configs.recommended.rules` wiring |\n| `packages/eslint-config/test-files/<fixture>/` | Optional fixture packages |\n| `packages/eslint-config/rules/_helpers/` | Shared helpers |\n\nPlugin namespace: `factory/<rule-name>`. The plugin is symlinked into `node_modules/eslint-plugin-factory` by the `setup` script -- presets register it automatically.\n\n## Workflow Diagram\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart TD\n  T[Ticket BAD/GOOD] --> S1[Step1 tests verbatim]\n  S1 --> S2[Step2 implement rule]\n  S2 --> R{Step1 tests pass?}\n  R -->|no| S2\n  R -->|yes| S3[Step3 sweep + triage]\n  S3 --> Q{<10% FP AND <=12 disables?}\n  Q -->|no| S2\n  Q -->|yes| S5[Step5 create-pr]\n  S5 --> S6[Step6 PR desc per exemplars]\n```\n\n## Step 1. Define motivating examples as tests, verbatim from the ticket\n\nWrite the tests first. Do not write rule code yet.\n\n1. Create `packages/eslint-config/rules/<name>.test.js` from `templates/rule.test.js.md`.\n2. Translate every BAD/GOOD example from the ticket into a `RuleTester` case:\n   - BAD example -> entry in the `invalid` array, asserted via `messageId`.\n   - GOOD example -> entry in the `valid` array.\n3. Keep each example **byte-for-byte identical** to the ticket. Do NOT normalize whitespace, rename identifiers, simplify, or \"clean up\" the source. Quote the ticket in a `// from FAC-XXXX:` comment above each case.\n4. Set `output: null` for every `invalid` case unless the rule is fixable. Always assert `messageId`, never raw message strings.\n5. Run the tests:\n   ```bash\n   cd packages/eslint-config && npm test -- <name>\n   ```\n   Every `invalid` test MUST fail (rule does not exist yet). If any passes here, your test is wrong -- a passing invalid test before implementation means the rule body is missing or misnamed.\n\n## Step 2. Fully implement the rule until every Step-1 test passes\n\n1. Scaffold `packages/eslint-config/rules/<name>.js` from `templates/rule.js.md`. Required pieces:\n   - `'use strict';`\n   - JSDoc header with rationale and BAD/GOOD examples.\n   - `meta.type` (`'problem'` for runtime hazards, `'suggestion'` for stylistic).\n   - `meta.docs.description` -- one sentence.\n   - `meta.messages` keyed by `messageId`.\n   - `meta.schema: []` unless the rule takes options.\n   - `meta.fixable` only if you provide an autofix.\n   - `create(context)` returning visitor functions.\n2. Register the rule in `packages/eslint-config/rules/index.js` (alphabetical or grouped, match existing style).\n3. Wire the rule into BOTH preset files -- omitting either breaks one set of consumers:\n   - `packages/eslint-config/factory.js` -- `rules` block.\n   - `packages/eslint-config/plugin.js` -- `configs.recommended.rules` block.\n4. Decide rollout severity:\n   - **Ship as `'error'` everywhere** when the violation count is small and you can fix all of them in this PR. Default choice.\n   - **Off-by-default migration** when the violation count is too large for one PR. Set `'off'` in both presets, then enable `'error'` in `apps/<x>/.eslintrc.js` for the apps that are already clean. Precedents: `factory/no-direct-process-env`, `factory/no-unsafe-json-parse`, `factory/no-error-status-response`.\n5. Iterate `cd packages/eslint-config && npm test` until every Step-1 case passes.\n\n### Cross-file rules\n\nIf the rule needs to read other repo files (e.g., parse a constants file, look up a sibling `package.json`), copy the cache + monorepo-root walk pattern from:\n- `rules/no-deprecated-feature-flag-references.js` -- reads `feature-flags/constants.ts`, walks up via `package.json.workspaces`.\n- `rules/no-self-package-import.js` -- finds nearest `package.json`, caches lookups per directory.\n\n### Test fixture packages\n\nIf a test case needs the rule to see a real `package.json` upstream, add a fixture package under `packages/eslint-config/test-files/<fixture>/` -- precedent: `test-files/self-import-pkg/package.json`.\n\n## Step 3. Run on the whole repo and triage every violation\n\nRun lint across every workspace that the rule touches and collect the FULL violation list. Note the `--`-before-`--filter` foot-gun -- without it, npm eats the flag and turbo runs every package (~9 GB RAM):\n\n```bash\n# Per workspace\nnpm run lint -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>\n\n# All workspaces (slow but exhaustive)\nnpm run lint\n```\n\nBuild a triage table -- one row per violation:\n\n| File | Line | Kind | Decision |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| `apps/backend/.../route.ts` | 42 | True positive, prod path | **Fix** as NOOP |\n| `apps/scripts/.../seed.ts` | 99 | True positive, non-prod path | **Carve out** in `factory.js` `overrides` OR inline `eslint-disable` (counts toward budget) |\n| `packages/x/.../foo.test.ts` | 17 | True positive, test-only | Carve out via `overrides` for `*.test.*` |\n| `packages/y/.../bar.ts` | 8 | False positive | **Refine rule** + add a `valid` test for this shape |\n\nDecision rules:\n- **True positive in production code** -> fix it (see \"NOOP fix discipline\" below).\n- **True positive in non-production / build / test path that is genuinely fine** -> prefer a category-wide `overrides` carve-out in `factory.js` over inline disables. Only use inline `// eslint-disable-next-line factory/<rule> -- <reason>` when the case is one-off. Inline disables count toward the Step-4 budget AND require codeowner approval (CI rule from PR #13331).\n- **False positive (rule reports something it should not)** -> add the offending shape as a new `valid` test case, then return to Step 2 and tighten the rule. Re-run Step 3.\n\nLoop Step 2 <-> Step 3 -- every false positive becomes a new `valid` test, every true negative the rule originally missed becomes a new `invalid` test.\n\n### NOOP fix discipline (REQUIRED)\n\nEvery true-positive fix MUST be a complete NOOP -- the program's observable behavior before and after the fix must be identical. Examples:\n\n- Replacing `process.env.X` with `getEnvironment().x` is a NOOP only if both resolve to the same value at runtime in every environment.\n- Replacing `as Foo` with a `Schema.parse(...)` is NOT a NOOP -- it adds runtime validation. That kind of fix belongs in a separate refactor PR, not in the rule-introduction PR.\n- Replacing `NextResponse.json({error}, {status: 400})` with `throw new ResponseError400BadRequest(...)` is NOOP only if `withGlobalWrap` middleware produces the byte-identical response shape and status. Verify the response payload before and after.\n\nIf a fix is not a NOOP, do NOT include it in this PR. Either:\n- Split the non-NOOP refactor into a separate PR that lands first, then return to Step 3.\n- Or add a temporary `eslint-disable` for the line, file an issue with the proper refactor, and land the rule with a slightly higher disable count (still subject to the Step-4 budget).\n\n### Granular commits (REQUIRED for review)\n\nLand the fixes as multiple narrow commits, not one mega-commit. Recommended split:\n\n1. **Commit 1**: rule + tests + index registration + preset wiring (no callsite changes). The rule is enabled but the repo may have failing lint -- that is expected at this commit and is the reviewer's anchor for understanding the rule's behavior.\n2. **Commit 2..N**: one commit per logical group of fixes -- by package, by call shape, or by file when fixes are independent. Each commit's diff should fit on a single screen if possible. Commit message format: `fix(<pkg>): <one-line description of the NOOP fix>`.\n3. **Final commit**: any preset `overrides` carve-outs and the final unfixable inline `eslint-disable`s with their justifications.\n\nReviewers can then approve commit-by-commit, and a bisect can pinpoint a regression to the exact fix.\n\n## Step 4. Quality gate -- iterate until the bar is met\n\nThe rule is **NOT ready** until ALL of the following hold across the full monorepo:\n\n- **False-positive disable rate < 10%** -- fewer than 10% of the original violation set required `eslint-disable` to silence. If higher, the rule is over-broad. Return to Step 2 and tighten it.\n- **Total `eslint-disable factory/<rule>` count <= 12** repo-wide. Count via:\n  ```bash\n  rg -n \"eslint-disable.*factory/<rule>\" | wc -l\n  ```\n  If higher, the rule is wrong-shaped or the convention itself is too aggressive. Stop and reconsider scope -- narrow the rule, split it, or ship as off-by-default.\n- `cd packages/eslint-config && npm test` -- clean.\n- For every affected workspace: `npm run lint -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>`, `npm run typecheck -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>`, `npm run test -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>` -- all clean.\n- `npm run knip` at repo root -- clean.\n\nIf any check fails, loop back. **Do NOT proceed to Step 5 with a rule that needs many disables -- that is the strongest signal the convention itself is wrong.**\n\n## Step 5. Ship the PR via `create-pr`\n\nPre-flight:\n- `git log origin/dev..HEAD --oneline` shows your commits and matches the granular split from Step 3.\n- Branch is pushed: `git push -u origin HEAD`.\n- Step-4 verification is green locally.\n\nInvoke the `create-pr` skill. It enforces base branch `dev`.\n\nTitle format (Conventional Commits):\n- `feat(eslint-config): add <rule-name> rule` -- when the rule ships from the eslint-config preset.\n- `feat(<scope>): new eslint rule to <verb>` -- when the rule is enabled only in a single app's `.eslintrc.js`. Precedent: `feat(backend): new eslint rule to ban nextjs error responses (#12638)`.\n\n## Step 6. Structure the PR description from the best historical examples\n\nThe strongest exemplars in this repo are **#13116** (`no-deprecated-feature-flag-references`) and **#10770** (`no-shell-injection`). Mirror their shape -- six elements, in this order:\n\n1. **One-line motivation** -- what bad pattern this rule bans.\n2. **Concrete production hazard** -- the runtime crash, prod regression, or security risk this prevents. Cite the issue / PR if there is one.\n   > From #13116: *\"... this is exactly how the SlackAutoRunHeadless prod regression in #12893 made it past review.\"*\n3. **What is skipped / exempted** -- test files, scripts, schema files, etc. Be specific.\n4. **Verification statement listing the workspaces actually checked** -- explicit, not vague.\n   > From #13116: *\"Verified against the full backend, web, cli, scripts, desktop, common, and frontend workspaces -- zero existing production-code violations.\"*\n5. **Test coverage stat** -- count of `valid` / `invalid` test cases.\n   > From #10770: *\"15 test cases covering valid/invalid patterns\"*\n6. **Edge cases handled** -- bullet list of tricky shapes the rule disambiguates (renamed imports, namespaces, optional chaining, computed property access, etc.).\n\nAlways close with `Closes FAC-XXXX` -- required by `docs/pre-pr-checklist.md`.\n\nA copy-pasteable template lives in `references.md`.\n\n## Don'ts\n\n- Don't write rule code before Step-1 tests are red.\n- Don't inline raw message strings in tests -- always assert via `messageId` so future copy edits don't break tests.\n- Don't ship a rule with `>= 12` `eslint-disable` exceptions repo-wide -- the convention is wrong-shaped, not the codebase.\n- Don't bundle non-NOOP refactors into the rule-introduction PR. Split them.\n- Don't squash the granular commits before merge -- the per-fix history is the review affordance.\n- Don't enable autofix when the fix would conflict with sibling rules. Document why in the rule header. Precedent: `rules/no-self-package-import.js` -- intentionally not autofixable because the correct fix conflicts with `factory/types-file-organization` and `factory/constants-file-organization`.\n- Don't run `npm run lint --filter=...` -- npm eats the flag (AGENTS.md). Always `npm run lint -- --filter=...`.\n- Don't forget to wire the rule into BOTH `factory.js` AND `plugin.js`.\n\n## Verification commands (cheat sheet)\n\n```bash\n# Rule unit tests\ncd packages/eslint-config && npm test\n\n# Per-workspace verification (note the -- before --filter)\nnpm run lint      -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>\nnpm run typecheck -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>\nnpm run test      -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>\n\n# Repo-wide\nnpm run knip\n\n# Count this rule's disables\nrg -n \"eslint-disable.*factory/<rule>\" | wc -l\n```\n\n## See Also\n\n- `templates/rule.js.md` -- rule scaffold to paste into `<name>.js`.\n- `templates/rule.test.js.md` -- RuleTester scaffold to paste into `<name>.test.js`.\n- `checklists.md` -- pre-merge gate.\n- `references.md` -- exemplar rules and PR descriptions.\n",
