          "text": "<system-notification>\nSkills provide specialized capabilities and domain knowledge. The user has selected the following skill for immediate execution. Begin following the skill's instructions now.\n<skill filePath=\"/Users/leo/.factory/plugins/cache/factory-mono-plugins/platform-ops/a6539202f86e/skills/create-lint-rule/SKILL.md\">\n<name>create-lint-rule</name>\n<description>Author a new custom ESLint rule in @factory/eslint-config using a strict TDD workflow, sweep the entire monorepo to fix every violation as a guaranteed NOOP, and ship it as a PR. Use when you need to enforce a new code-quality convention via lint. Not for fixing violations of existing rules -- use ban-type-assertions, process-env-migration, no-use-effect, or fix-knip-unused-exports instead.\n (project)</description>\n# Create Lint Rule\n\nAuthor a new `factory/<rule-name>` ESLint rule, sweep the monorepo to zero existing violations, and ship the PR. The workflow is strict TDD: tests come from the ticket verbatim, then implementation, then a triaged repo-wide sweep, then a hard quality gate.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- You need to enforce a new code-quality convention via lint.\n- You have BAD/GOOD examples in a ticket or design doc that describe the convention.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- Fixing violations of an already-existing rule -- use the dedicated fix skills:\n  - `ban-type-assertions` -- replace `as` casts.\n  - `process-env-migration` -- migrate `process.env` to `@factory/environment`.\n  - `no-use-effect` -- replace `useEffect` calls.\n  - `fix-knip-unused-exports` -- fix knip unused-exports violations.\n- Tweaking an existing custom rule -- edit the rule + its test file directly.\n\n## Quick Reference\n\n| Where | What |\n| --- | --- |\n| `packages/eslint-config/rules/<name>.js` | Rule source |\n| `packages/eslint-config/rules/<name>.test.js` | RuleTester unit tests |\n| `packages/eslint-config/rules/index.js` | Rule registration |\n| `packages/eslint-config/factory.js` | Base preset wiring |\n| `packages/eslint-config/plugin.js` | `configs.recommended.rules` wiring |\n| `packages/eslint-config/test-files/<fixture>/` | Optional fixture packages |\n| `packages/eslint-config/rules/_helpers/` | Shared helpers |\n\nPlugin namespace: `factory/<rule-name>`. The plugin is symlinked into `node_modules/eslint-plugin-factory` by the `setup` script -- presets register it automatically.\n\n## Workflow Diagram\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart TD\n  T[Ticket BAD/GOOD] --> S1[Step1 tests verbatim]\n  S1 --> S2[Step2 implement rule]\n  S2 --> R{Step1 tests pass?}\n  R -->|no| S2\n  R -->|yes| S3[Step3 sweep + triage]\n  S3 --> Q{<10% FP AND <=12 disables?}\n  Q -->|no| S2\n  Q -->|yes| S5[Step5 create-pr]\n  S5 --> S6[Step6 PR desc per exemplars]\n```\n\n## Step 1. Define motivating examples as tests, verbatim from the ticket\n\nWrite the tests first. Do not write rule code yet.\n\n1. Create `packages/eslint-config/rules/<name>.test.js` from `templates/rule.test.js.md`.\n2. Translate every BAD/GOOD example from the ticket into a `RuleTester` case:\n   - BAD example -> entry in the `invalid` array, asserted via `messageId`.\n   - GOOD example -> entry in the `valid` array.\n3. Keep each example **byte-for-byte identical** to the ticket. Do NOT normalize whitespace, rename identifiers, simplify, or \"clean up\" the source. Quote the ticket in a `// from FAC-XXXX:` comment above each case.\n4. Set `output: null` for every `invalid` case unless the rule is fixable. Always assert `messageId`, never raw message strings.\n5. Run the tests:\n   ```bash\n   cd packages/eslint-config && npm test -- <name>\n   ```\n   Every `invalid` test MUST fail (rule does not exist yet). If any passes here, your test is wrong -- a passing invalid test before implementation means the rule body is missing or misnamed.\n\n## Step 2. Fully implement the rule until every Step-1 test passes\n\n1. Scaffold `packages/eslint-config/rules/<name>.js` from `templates/rule.js.md`. Required pieces:\n   - `'use strict';`\n   - JSDoc header with rationale and BAD/GOOD examples.\n   - `meta.type` (`'problem'` for runtime hazards, `'suggestion'` for stylistic).\n   - `meta.docs.description` -- one sentence.\n   - `meta.messages` keyed by `messageId`.\n   - `meta.schema: []` unless the rule takes options.\n   - `meta.fixable` only if you provide an autofix.\n   - `create(context)` returning visitor functions.\n2. Register the rule in `packages/eslint-config/rules/index.js` (alphabetical or grouped, match existing style).\n3. Wire the rule into BOTH preset files -- omitting either breaks one set of consumers:\n   - `packages/eslint-config/factory.js` -- `rules` block.\n   - `packages/eslint-config/plugin.js` -- `configs.recommended.rules` block.\n4. Decide rollout severity:\n   - **Ship as `'error'` everywhere** when the violation count is small and you can fix all of them in this PR. Default choice.\n   - **Off-by-default migration** when the violation count is too large for one PR. Set `'off'` in both presets, then enable `'error'` in `apps/<x>/.eslintrc.js` for the apps that are already clean. Precedents: `factory/no-direct-process-env`, `factory/no-unsafe-json-parse`, `factory/no-error-status-response`.\n5. Iterate `cd packages/eslint-config && npm test` until every Step-1 case passes.\n\n### Cross-file rules\n\nIf the rule needs to read other repo files (e.g., parse a constants file, look up a sibling `package.json`), copy the cache + monorepo-root walk pattern from:\n- `rules/no-deprecated-feature-flag-references.js` -- reads `feature-flags/constants.ts`, walks up via `package.json.workspaces`.\n- `rules/no-self-package-import.js` -- finds nearest `package.json`, caches lookups per directory.\n\n### Test fixture packages\n\nIf a test case needs the rule to see a real `package.json` upstream, add a fixture package under `packages/eslint-config/test-files/<fixture>/` -- precedent: `test-files/self-import-pkg/package.json`.\n\n## Step 3. Run on the whole repo and triage every violation\n\nRun lint across every workspace that the rule touches and collect the FULL violation list. Note the `--`-before-`--filter` foot-gun -- without it, npm eats the flag and turbo runs every package (~9 GB RAM):\n\n```bash\n# Per workspace\nnpm run lint -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>\n\n# All workspaces (slow but exhaustive)\nnpm run lint\n```\n\nBuild a triage table -- one row per violation:\n\n| File | Line | Kind | Decision |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| `apps/backend/.../route.ts` | 42 | True positive, prod path | **Fix** as NOOP |\n| `apps/scripts/.../seed.ts` | 99 | True positive, non-prod path | **Carve out** in `factory.js` `overrides` OR inline `eslint-disable` (counts toward budget) |\n| `packages/x/.../foo.test.ts` | 17 | True positive, test-only | Carve out via `overrides` for `*.test.*` |\n| `packages/y/.../bar.ts` | 8 | False positive | **Refine rule** + add a `valid` test for this shape |\n\nDecision rules:\n- **True positive in production code** -> fix it (see \"NOOP fix discipline\" below).\n- **True positive in non-production / build / test path that is genuinely fine** -> prefer a category-wide `overrides` carve-out in `factory.js` over inline disables. Only use inline `// eslint-disable-next-line factory/<rule> -- <reason>` when the case is one-off. Inline disables count toward the Step-4 budget AND require codeowner approval (CI rule from PR #13331).\n- **False positive (rule reports something it should not)** -> add the offending shape as a new `valid` test case, then return to Step 2 and tighten the rule. Re-run Step 3.\n\nLoop Step 2 <-> Step 3 -- every false positive becomes a new `valid` test, every true negative the rule originally missed becomes a new `invalid` test.\n\n### NOOP fix discipline (REQUIRED)\n\nEvery true-positive fix MUST be a complete NOOP -- the program's observable behavior before and after the fix must be identical. Examples:\n\n- Replacing `process.env.X` with `getEnvironment().x` is a NOOP onl