            "new_str": "### NOOP fix discipline (depends on rule class)\n\nWhat counts as a \"safe fix\" depends on the rule's class from the top of this doc.\n\n**Correctness rule fixes MUST be NOOP** -- program's observable behavior is identical before and after.\n- `process.env.X` -> `getEnvironment().x` is NOOP only if both resolve to the same value at runtime in every environment.\n- `as Foo` -> `Schema.parse(...)` is NOT NOOP (adds runtime validation). Split into a separate refactor PR that lands first.\n- `NextResponse.json({error}, {status: 400})` -> `throw new ResponseError400BadRequest(...)` is NOOP only if `withGlobalWrap` middleware produces the byte-identical response shape and status -- verify the payload before and after.\n\nIf a correctness-rule fix is not a NOOP, do NOT include it. Either split the refactor or add a temporary `eslint-disable` with a TODO.\n\n**Deprecation rule fixes INTEND to change behavior** -- that's why the rule exists.\n- `Promise.all(list.map(fn))` -> sequential `for await` changes wall time (slower), error semantics (first-rejection vs first-thrown), and concurrency (unbounded -> 1). Those changes are the point.\n- `useEffect(() => setX(deriveFromY(y)), [y])` -> inline computation changes the render cycle (two renders -> one). That's the fix.\n- `NEW_FETCH(...)` -> `fetchWithRetries(...)` changes retry behavior. Required.\n\nFor deprecation rules, \"safe fix\" means: **preserves the same correctness contract** but adopts the new convention's behavior tradeoffs. Concretely:\n- Per-item work is still performed (sequential for-of still iterates every item).\n- Failure semantics still surface (sequential `for await` + try/catch still logs each rejection; `Promise.allSettled` -> `for-of` + per-item try/catch preserves the \"continue past failures\" contract).\n- Side-effect order is preserved or improved (sequential is *more* deterministic than parallel).\n\nWhen the fix would meaningfully change a contract that callers depend on (e.g., a downstream consumer awaits the first rejection and uses it for control flow), that callsite is an `eslint-disable` candidate, not a fix candidate. Document why on the disable line.",
