            "new_str": "## Step 4. Quality gate -- iterate until the bar is met\n\nThe bar depends on the rule's class.\n\n### Universal gates (both classes)\n\n- `cd packages/eslint-config && npm test` -- clean.\n- For every affected workspace: `npm run lint -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>`, `npm run typecheck -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>`, `npm run test -- --filter=@factory/<pkg>` -- all clean.\n- `npm run knip` at repo root -- clean.\n- Every `eslint-disable factory/<rule>` carries a `-- <reason>` justification a reviewer can accept (CI rule from PR #13331 requires codeowner approval for any disable).\n\nCount disables:\n```bash\nrg -n \"eslint-disable.*factory/<rule>\" | wc -l\n```\n\n### Correctness rule gate\n\n- **False-positive disable rate < 10%** of the original violation set.\n- **Total disables <= 12** repo-wide. If higher, the rule is wrong-shaped. Return to Step 2 and tighten it, or split the rule.\n- Repo is at 0 violations of the new rule.\n\n### Deprecation rule gate\n\n- **No disable cap.** Each disable is a per-site call, not a signal the rule is wrong.\n- Repo is at 0 violations of the new rule (every callsite is either fixed or disabled with a justification).\n- The disables-vs-fixes ratio should match the user's stated intent. PLT-51's stated intent was \"ban it, force eslint-disable for legacy\" -- shipping at 87 disables / 132 fixes was the intent. If a correctness-flavor rule ended up at >50% disables, reclassify and revisit.\n\n### Iterative shipping gate (correctness OR deprecation)\n\nWhen you split into multiple PRs (the third rollout option), each PR's gate is:\n- The packages cleaned in this PR are at 0 violations.\n- The packages NOT yet cleaned have the rule `'off'` in their `.eslintrc.js` with a `TODO(<TICKET>)` comment naming the follow-up PR.\n- Rule-introduction PR-1 carries the rule definition + tests + the smallest packages. Follow-up PRs are pure callsite sweeps with no rule changes.\n\nIf any check fails, loop back.",
