            "new_str": "## `eslint-disable-next-line` placement (the most common gotcha)\n\nThe disable comment must be on the line **directly above the line the rule reports on**, which for `await Promise.all(...)` / similar is the `await` line, not the `const [...] = ...` destructure line above it. Always re-run lint after adding a disable to confirm it suppressed the right line.\n\n```ts\n// WRONG -- rule fires on the await Promise.all line, not the const line:\n// eslint-disable-next-line factory/no-promise-all -- ...\nconst [a, b, c, d, e] = await Promise.all([...]);\n\n// RIGHT -- disable directly above the line the rule reports:\nconst [a, b, c, d, e] =\n  // eslint-disable-next-line factory/no-promise-all -- ...\n  await Promise.all([...]);\n\n// ALSO RIGHT for multi-line destructure -- inside the destructure:\nconst [\n  a, b, c, d, e,\n  // eslint-disable-next-line factory/no-promise-all -- ...\n] = await Promise.all([...]);\n```\n\nIf `npm run lint` reports `'factory/<rule>' rule is disabled but never reported` for your disable comment, you placed it on the wrong line.\n\n### Sibling rules that often co-fire when sequentializing\n\nWhen converting a parallel fan-out to sequential, the surrounding code often trips other rules. Plan for these:\n\n- `factory/require-catch-handling`: empty `catch {}` from a sequentialized `Promise.allSettled` will fire. Replace with `catch (err) { logWarn(...) }` or `catch (err) { /* explicit ignore */ }` plus an unused-var disable.\n- `import/order`: a new `promisePool` import needs alphabetical placement against existing `@factory/*` imports.\n- `factory/types-file-organization` / `factory/constants-file-organization`: extracting an inline type or constant during the refactor will fire -- inline it instead, or move it to the right file.\n\n## Don'ts\n\n- Don't write rule code before Step-1 tests are red.\n- Don't inline raw message strings in tests -- always assert via `messageId` so future copy edits don't break tests.\n- 