            "content": "## Description\n\nAdds `factory/no-promise-all` -- bans OOM-hazardous `Promise.all` and `Promise.allSettled` callsites and sweeps every existing offender across the monorepo.\n\nThe rule was originally written to ban `Promise.all` outright, but was narrowed during implementation (Step 2.5 of `create-lint-rule`) to flag only the OOM-hazard subset: variable inputs (potentially unbounded), `.map()` callers, array spreads, and array literals with 4+ elements. Test files are entirely exempt. The narrowing cut the violation count from 414 callsites to 219.\n\n### Rationale (PLT-51)\n\n- **Agents pattern-match `Promise.all` everywhere**, including spots where operations have ordering dependencies or auth invariants. Running auth concurrently with the next step is a real security hazard observed in review.\n- **Stack traces from inside `Promise.all` arms are lost in Sentry**, which kills debuggability of production failures.\n- **`Promise.all(list.map(fn))` is unbounded concurrency** and has caused OOM cron crashes in production: \"I've actually found a ton of OOM cron crashes because we did that!! we had unbounded concurrency.\"\n\nFor the rare legitimate concurrent case, callers use the existing `promisePool` helper in `@factory/utils` (bounded concurrency, structured errors) or add `// eslint-disable-next-line factory/no-promise-all -- <reason>`.\n\n### Skips / exempted\n\n- Test files (`*.test.*`, `*.spec.*`, `__tests__/`, `test-utils/`, `__mocks__/`) -- the rule does not fire at all on these.\n- Array literals with 1-3 concrete elements -- the parallel-fetch-two-things pattern stays NOOP-free.\n- `Promise.race` and `Promise.any` are not banned.\n- `Promise.resolve` / `Promise.reject` are not banned.\n\n### Verification\n\nVerified against the full **updater, runtime, droid-core, daemon-client, component-library, daemon-core, desktop, factory-vscode-extension, frontend, services, backend, and cli** workspaces -- zero remaining `factory/no-promise-all` lint errors after the sweep.\n\n- **26 test cases** covering valid / invalid patterns (test files exempt, allowed small fixed-arity, banned variable / `.map()` / spread / 4+ element / Promise.allSettled).\n- **219 callsites triaged** under the narrowed rule: ~132 converted to sequential `await` / `promisePool` / for-of, ~87 retained with `eslint-disable-next-line factory/no-promise-all -- <reason>`.\n- **12 commits** split per package (1 rule-introduction commit + 11 per-package fix commits) so the diff can be reviewed commit by commit.\n\n### Edge cases handled by the rule\n\n- Computed `Promise['all'](...)` access is intentionally NOT flagged (rare; the static-analysis surface isn't worth the false-positive risk).\n- Reading the function reference without calling it (`const fn = Promise.all`) is not flagged.\n- Test-file detection covers both filename (`*.test.*`, `*.spec.*`) and path segments (`__tests__/`, `test-utils/`, `__mocks__/`).\n- Array literals with a `...spread` element are treated as unbounded even if they have <=3 explicit positions.\n- Both `Promise.all` and `Promise.allSettled` are banned identically under the same threshold (same OOM concern).\n\n### Notes for reviewers\n\n- **Commits should NOT be squashed** before merge. The per-package commit history is the review affordance; bisecting any future regression points directly at the offending callsite group.\n- Every `eslint-disable factory/no-promise-all` in this PR carries a `-- <reason>` explaining why the parallelism is intentional (telemetry fan-out, hand-rolled bounded pool, race-against-deadline, fixed-arity startup fanout, etc.). Per the `create-lint-rule` skill's deprecation-rule gate, those disables are expected -- this is a deprecation rule, not a correctness rule.\n\n## Related Issue\n\nCloses PLT-51\n\n## Potential Risk & Impact\n\n- **Behavior changes are intentional.** Every sequential conversion in this PR changes wall time (slower), concurrency semantics (1 vs N), and (for `Promise.allSettled` -> for-of + try/catch) error-collection shape. These changes are the explicit point of the rule -- see Rationale above.\n- **Sentinel cases that COULD regress wall-time UX**: `runNetworkDiagnostics` (desktop), `runChatStream` tracking finalization, MCP server list operations. All retained as `eslint-disable` to preserve their parallel semantics.\n- **OOM exposure** previously called out by the ticket is eliminated at the swept sites: unbounded `Promise.all(list.map(fn))` is gone from production code paths in the listed packages.\n\n## How Has This Been Tested?\n\n- `cd packages/eslint-config && npm test` -- 684 tests pass (rule has 26 unit tests).\n- `npm run lint -- --filter=@factory/<each affected pkg>` -- clean for all 12 affected packages.\n- `npm run typecheck -- --filter=@factory/<each affected pkg>` -- clean (CLI baseline pre-existing errors unchanged).\n- `npm run lint` repo-wide -- zero `factory/no-promise-all` errors remaining.\n\n## Backwards Compatibility\n\nN/A internally -- this is a lint rule + callsite refactors. No public API, response shape, protocol message, or persisted data format changed.\n\nThe behavior changes at fixed callsites (sequential vs parallel) are observable to downstream consumers only if they previously depended on the parallel scheduling for ordering or timing. Those callsites are exactly the ones we keep as `eslint-disable` with explicit justification.\n",
